We all want LLMs to collaborate with humans to help them achieve their goals. But LLMs are not trained to collaborate, they are trained to imitate. Can we teach LM agents to help humans by first making them help each other? 

arxiv.org/abs/2503.14481

We focus on two capabilities: knowing when to use a costly retrieval tool, and hedging non-confident answers. To teach these capabilities, we create a small multi-agent society, in which two "helpers" can use specialized retrieval tools to pass information back to an "asker"

Because the identity of each helper is hidden from the asker, it is forced to rely on confidence signals when faced with incompatible answers from the helpers. Maximizing effort-penalized accuracy of the full rollout can teach the LLM to use these confidence markers correctly.

A bit of game theory can help explain when this can work: we model the setup as a game of public utility provision, where the public utility is the extra information provided by the costly retrieval action. The game has a unique equilibrium when the tools are sufficiently distinct (or both bad).
In practice, collaborative self-play + reinforced self-training (ReST) lead to improved task performance, better calibration of confidence markers, and more efficient tool use.
An ablation reveals the importance of mechanism design: when the helper identities are known to the asker during training (CSP-DeAnon), calibrated hedging is no longer learned.

I offer no investment advice and make no predictions.  But to those of you rejoicing in the recent stock market rally which has the S&P 500 up over 1% today as I write I will point  out that bear market rallies are historically a frequent phenomenon.

After the crash of  October 24, 1929, by the spring of 1930 major market indicators  were roughly equal to their values in the spring of 1929  (but not equal to their pre crash values!).  Whether we are in a Donald Trump bear market I cannot say.
Elon Musk has described Social Security as a great Ponzi scheme.  This is not not true!  What is a great Ponzi scheme, perhaps the greatest Ponzi scheme of all time is the U.S. stock market.

Ostensibly, stock prices are based on earnings representing the dividends (income) a corporation could pay out now or at some point in the forseeable future.  (PE ratio is calclulated by dividing a stock's market price by the corporation's earnings per share). This is the big lie!
Here's a quick Google:  "Tesla PE ratio as of March 23, 2025 is 175.8"  There is no rational justification of Tesla's stock price based on its earnings.
To  give equal time to another of the miraculous seven:  "As of March 23, 2025, NVIDIA's trailing twelve-month (TTM) P/E ratio is approximately 40.03."
Social Security approaches crisis  while the stock market has achieved an illusionary  escape velocity because Republicans trash Social Security while starving it of tax revenue

(there is no justification for the current Social Security wage base limit of  $176,100) ; and simultaneously Republicans pump up the stock market grift with rhetoric and tax policy. "A fool and his money are soon parted."  How soon I cannot say.

And in fact there *should* be input into science from outside the field, because it doesn't exist in a vacuum any more than defense or education or business or religion or any other large-scale area of human endeavour.
But if there's a better way to keep science more or less on track, I'll be damned if I know what it is.

The only people qualified to judge the work of scientists‚Äînot the big-picture priorities, and not the utility of the results, but the nitty-gritty of the work itself‚Äîare other people knowledgeable in the same line of work, and I don't see that changing.  Same as any other job, really.
Like I said above, there are proposals for addressing peer review's flaws, and I'll be happy to expound on that if anyone likes.
